H2H Satisfaction Survey Results Overview

Summary Results Report by Olivia McCargar

Question 1

Overall, how satisfied are you with the H2H Network to date?

Please rank 1 not at all satisfied and 5 is very satisfied.














Comments on This Question

GNC Technical Alliance, Technical Support Team

Score:4
I really value the network in general, but wish that we had more time to engage. Sometimes dont feel like we are the right fit for the network, but do also feel very welcomed.

Global Public Policy Institute (GPPi)

Score:3
I continue to support the H2H idea, but it became clear over time that the network is much less relevant to our work than I initially thought.

DAHLIA

Score:2
We are not involved enough to be specific, our expertise is evaluation, communication which are fields for which we dont have much info or feedback from H2H

CALP Network

Score:4
We are not significantly engaged in the H2H Network but we do appreciate H2H efforts and resources available within the system.

The Geneva Learning Foundation

Score:4
Not very involved, but glad H2H exists and it looks from afar as if it is useful to members. Still believe its very much needed.

Humanitarian Academy for Development

Score:3
Positive feedback: When projects are live, H2H are a very supportive, flexible, and professional client to work with. Areas for improvement: Funding calls are often delayed following an emergency, tight timeframe to apply once announced, extensive application requirements, funding amounts often quite small, and there is a lot of competition for each call.

RE:ACT Disaster Response

Score:4
We have not yet fully utilised the services the network provides and am seeking to better understand and do more together.

Edge Effect

Score:3
We often cannot talk part in calls that occur in the wee hours in Australia, or in-person events like HNPW for which we have no funds to travel. As a social enterprise we are ineligible for funding through H2H, which limits what we can do. We have had limited corss-learning or partnership development opportunities with other H2H members, due in large part to those 2 factors. We hope to do more.

Humanitarian Logistics Association

Score:4
Very much value H2H membership and being part of a potentially change building network. H2H should communicate its position and value more widely

GISF

Score:3
So far we have not applied for H2H funding

iMMAP France

Score:3
iMMAP appreciates the support provided by the H2H network to kick-off new projects, especially in the context of sudden crises. In the meanwhile, the short duration of the projects combined with the financial and administrative requirements (e.g.small envelopes per project, financial reports to be provided for a 3-month project, impossibility to procure assets, threshold of the DSA rates, specific exchange rate to be used) bring some difficulties for the teams to develop and implement the actions.

The New Humanitarian

Score:5
The H2H Network has been a great resource of support for us to be able to respond faster and better as a crisis occurs. In addition, the community aspect and resources like the crisis watch calls and Slack have been very useful for us to be aware of what others are doing, towards informing our journalism and considering potential collaborations.

Medical Aid films

Score:5
excellent and proactive network - thank you

CLEAR Global

Score:4
The H2H team is a good advocate for the value of member services in emergencies; theres real value in supporting collaboration and coordination between members, including through funding; the H2H Fund has got quality support into early-phase responses where it would never otherwise have been; it would be good to find ways to build the evidence and analysis better collectively, but that is also a resource issue.

DEMAC

Score:4
We appreciate the regular information and meetings from H2H

Ground Truth Solutions

Score:4
Helpful for making us aware of other H2H orgs, funding, thinking outside the box

Humanitarian OpenStreetMap Team (HOT)

Score:3
The granting application process is very long considering limited amount of funds being distributed. Reporting is also quite demanding. Access to other organizations is a plus

Livestock Emergency Guidelines and Standards - LEGS

Score:3
Were very supportive of the H2H Network, but find we sometimes slip through the gaps in terms of more active engagement with other members and the Network itself, because we are not operational.

Evidence Aid

Score:4
We struggle with time commitment vs.support from H2H

BBC Media Action

Score:3
Not always clear what criteria are for deciding how members are funded.

Humanitarian Advisory Group

Score:4
We love the information we get from H2H, the time difference makes it hard for us to be more engaged.

Aviation Sans Frontires International

Score:3
We feel that the added value we may bring into the humanitarian sector, especially last mile air transport and about accontability and efficiency of the humanitarian air transport sector has never been understood so far by the H2H Network management. We feel also that priority is given to soft services (mapping, communication, etc., which are obviously important but other types of services are equally important. The delays to respond to funding proposals are too short and scoping mission (e.g.DRC) are disapearing.

Insecurity Insight

Score:5
I find H2H very response to what members say. It also provides excellent learning and networking opportunities

Data Friendly Space

Score:5
H2H is doing important work to develop collaborative responses to emergent situations.

MapAction

Score:4
H2H needs to do more to promote the interests of its members (access to donors and core funding, access to humanitarian situations and global partners) for its members. Needs to look less like an NGO carving its own niche.

Groupe URD

Score:4
We dont have yet many H2H projects - to be continued

CartONG

Score:4
Grant mechanism provides new opportunities; visibility great; experience sharing interesting; could improve on joint projects with members

Sphere

Score:4
Very positive engagement with H2h. Community of practice element is strong as well as trainings. Work around activations also important

Research-Aid Networks

Score:4
It is a great resource bringing organizations together. We have found several new partners and projects though and with other H2H members. It would be helpful though to have more facilitated opportunities to network, learn about and interact with other member orgs.

Relief Applications

Score:5
We see it as an opportunity to create collaborations and find funding opportunities together.

Statistics Without Borders

Score:5
Its a great team of organizations and periodically SWB is able to contribute and assist members.

Internews

Score:4
H2H builds relationships between agencies that can become relevant at a time of a crisis, but also helps set the agenda of the wider humanitarian system outside a particular response

Fondation Hirondelle

Score:3
H2H faced many challenges (change of people) and it remains difficult to get new donors

Groundwater Relief

Score:5
We are very happy to be a part of a network of specialist organisations supporting humanitarian interventions that can also help finance these through obtaining larger packets of money from large institutional donors

HQAI

Score:3
we do not sufficiently take advantage of the network at this stage. the accelerator fund seems to be an interesting tool and we need to get in touch to learn more and get involved. We can see increasing communication and activity from the H2H team, it is rather our team that is lacking time to get sufficiently involved. We believe that there could be a role for H2H in partnership brokering between members.

Humanitarian Advisory Group

Aviation Sans Frontires International
Since years we are working on a new approach of humanitarian last mile air transport which is making NGO (benefiting from the transport) the core of aviation Project Cycle Management, introducing new paradigms and developing methodologies for need and impact assessment. This should help to increase accountability not only in the air transport sector but also in all logistics sectors. Indeed, what we do is to measure the impact of our service to the capacity of the benefiting NGO to be more efficient in the field, and this approch does not seems to exist in the recently published logistics humanitarian standards. It was clearly explained when we participated to the accelerator funds but we have been dismissed because we have proposed a new app to assess NGO needs remotely with an innovative approach (a game on airline management transformed into an assessment tool) but we have been told that app are not innovation. Currently, we are setting up -a last mile humanitarian air service for local medical organizations using local air operators in eastern DRC and this is showing that there are still huge needs to be covered in last mile aviation beside what United Nations Humanitarian Air Services is doing.
Insecurity Insight
Finance management
